Columbia police warn residents of scam alert, person posing as an officer

by Kyreon Lee

Sat, December 29th 2018 at 3:37 PM
Updated Sun, December 30th 2018 at 6:54 PM
Columbia Police Department warn residents of scam alert. (File).

    TOPICS:

    Advance-fee ScamColumbia Police DepartmentConfidence TricksCrimeDeceptionFraudHuman behaviorLaw enforcement

COLUMBIA — The Columbia Police Department warned residents on Saturday of a scam alert regarding a person posing as an officer from the department. The person identified as a male has made calls and informed residents that they have warrants and should send money in order to avoid being arrested.

The department said it would never call and ask for money to resolve a warrant.

The Boone County Sheriff's Department experienced a similar scam late last week, after received reports about residents getting calls from a detective that threatened arrest for failure to appear for jury duty.

The scammer identified himself as the department's Detective Tom O'Sullivan. He used the names Detective Sullivan or Detective O’Sullivan. One person was told by the scammer that a payment of $1,700 was required to cancel an outstanding warrant.

The department said it would never contact residents asking them to provide financial information over the telephone to pay a fine or cancel a warrant. People who received calls were asked to immediately hang up and contact law enforcement at 3-1-1.
